text: This place is an institution.  The wings are absolutely out of this world good. Always a good size, done correctly, and covered with your choice of incredible sauce.  You can keep it mild and order "7s" or you can crank up the heat and order "15s" or hotter.  A good seat here is always a hot commodity so come early or call ahead and take some to go.  A must try while in Grand Forks.

text:
I have it on good authority that these are the best Buffalo style hot wings outside of Buffalo, NY. My dad spent 4 years and graduated high school in Buffalo NY in '79. He learned how to make them while living there as well; what I'm saying is he knows Buffalo Wings. I brought him here when he was visiting and had him try the shark sauce and Buffalo. He was impressed with not only the taste, but by how much meat was on the wing and how hot (temperature) they were. 10/10 both he and I would recommend the wings that this place is known for.
They do have other menu items, most of which I've heard are good, but can't personally say myself. Their sides however, are also killer. Some Cajun fries to scoop up all the extra wing sauce is a great choice.

text:
Tiny little hole in the wall with fantastic wings.
If you don't get here early be prepared to wait. The place is small and the fans are loyal.
Prices are reasonable and service is pretty good considering everybody shows up and orders at the same time so the kitchen must be crazy. Once the initial rush calms down things seem much smoother.
The wings are what they're known for and are meaty and have a wide variety. Choose different levels of heat, sauces, flavors, there's something for everyone. The lavosh is quite good too.

text:
The Parrot's Cay is a real hidden gem in Grand Forks. They are famous for their spectacular hot wings, with heat levels varying from mild to wild. They also have lavoshes, jambalaya, and po boys on the menu that are quite good as well.

There is almost always a wait, unless you get there as soon as they open, but you can call ahead for a takeout order and get in and out quite quickly, if need be.

text:
I have had wings from all over the US, from mom and pop shops to large national chains, and everything in between. I came into grand forks for a wedding and one of the guests wouldn't stop raving about parrots cay wings. Thinking that there was no way they could be THAT good, I reluctantly stopped in to try these wings. First impressions were great, loved the divey feel of the place and brought me back to my college days. Tap beer list, nothing really worth writing home about, but they have the standards you would expect at a divey college bar.  Then the wings. The first thing I noticed is they didnt use franks out of the bottle, second thing was that the wings were phenomenal.  The wings were perfectly crispy on the outside, yet still juicy on the inside. The buffalo sauce was flavorful, and spicy, but not to the point of ruining your taste buds for the rest of the meal. The wings came with a cup of ranch, which wasn't needed because the sauce was just that good.

So major props to cays.  If I ever find myself back in grand forks, this will 100% be a place to visit again.

text:
Cozy environment & friendly staff! If you think 'the other guys' hot wings aren't that hot, come on in, they have variable heat levels and the top ones will make you sweat.

There is also a Touchtunes jukebox. You can control it from your phone, so no one needs to know it's you playing Swedish Folk Metal.

Daily Specials:
Happy hour all day Monday, jambalaya bowl on special
Tuesday (most) all taps/bottles, and select po-boy sandwich on special
Wed/Thur domestic pitcher and full order of wings on special
Fri/Sat rotating drink specials
Closed on Sundays

text: You're really messing up if you love wings and you havent been to this place, their wing sauces are unique and delicious, and they are  unlike anywhere else I've ever had. The place is a little divey and it's always packed on wednesdays and Thursdays, I recommend showing up right when they open on those days since it's a bit of a smaller venue. Their cajun pasta and jambalaya are also very good main dishes. I usually get a side of fries with my wings which are also very tasty.

text: With a place this good... expect a wait. Every day they open at 4:30 PM and there is a line out the door. The location is a small "hole-in-the-wall" and all meals are served on paper plates and plastic silverware so don't expect anything fancy. But you won't find better wings in the entire midwest. Their famous "Shark wings" are a blend of their original and BBQ sauces that is the best sauce I've ever had and you get to choose the heat on a 1-40 scale. If you like the sauce as much as I do you can order a batch of sauce to take home.

text:
We stopped there for a late dinner on a Saturday night. We were seated shortly after walking in and noticed they have a ton of beers on tap. The service was decent and there weren't too many people there. Once were placed our order, it took over an hour to arrive. The server mentioned after about 45 minutes that it's been slow service in the kitchen that night, but I would have appreciated a warning before I ordered.

Once the food came, it tasted delicious. The wait was absolutely worth it. I tried the bbq wings, the shrimp, crawdads, and fried alligator. All magnificent but I'll probably get the wings again!

text:
Now I like the Parrots Cay as much as the next person and I have ordered the same shark wings every time I have gone in. Twice it has happened that I have ordered the shark wings and received their regular buffalo wings instead. Now I work at a restaurant and I know how busy it gets and how stressful it gets as well, but what happened next really puts a damper on my experience. I waited until the server came around and she asked if anything was wrong and I stated that I ordered the shark wings and not the buffalo wings. Her response was "you didn't order the shark wings but I will have them make new ones."

I was dumbfounded. As stated above, I have ordered the same thing every single time without changing and the server is accusing me of being wrong. NEVER should a server say that to a customer. We would get reprimanded big time where I work if we did this. I get it, yes it is noisy and it is hard to hear but come on, take some responsibility.

The second time it happened I simply stated the same that I ordered the shark but got the regular buffalo and said it was no big deal that if I could just simply get a side of the shark, I would be fine. Again I was accused of ordering something I didn't order and said she would have to charge me for the side of sauce or I could just have them remake it.

Well right there is one of the dumbest things I have heard. I had them remake it and waste the wings the buffalo sauce and make new wings instead of just getting a side of shark sauce.

The service is lacking big time and if it weren't for the great food, I would not go back and the place would be gone by now in all honesty I'm sure.

text:
The Best Wings anywhere! And I've looked all over the world. The Parrot's Cay is a cajun dive bar in Grand Forks ND, let that sink in for a minute. It's the type of place that would be on Diners and Dives if they ever came to North Dakota. Their cajun buffalo sauce is the best I've ever had. Their shark sauce wings won first place in Buffalo NY.
The wings all have an adjustable heat level, based on a number scale that ranges from 3-30. Most people would probably want to start at a 7 on that scale. The heat challenges get insane. They also serve Lavash, Crawdads, Pasta and Po'boys. But the wings are the star of the show.

The Cay has the best food you can get in the entire state of North Dakota, and that isn't even a compliment. Grand Forks is a college town, so this place can get packed often. It's a bar, so you have to be 21 to enter. Tons of beers on tap. Enjoy.

text:
Unfortunately, the Saturday night bands and the Tuesday night Cay Jams are now a thing of the past, but they still do Thursday karaoke, if I'm not mistaken.  The menu is still an attraction, as well as the dozen or so beers on tap.  Patronage ranges between after-work crowd, students, and hippies.

text: The staff is usually very helpful. My meals here have always been hit or miss. Most likely just personal preference on my part.  For instance the cheese plate is always amazing.  The bison meatloaf is also very good but too rich for my taste.  The truffle fries, also good but very rich.  Don't order them unless you have someone, or three, to share with.  Last time I was there I had the Duet of Duck.  The leg was fantastic but the breast was just too greasy and funny tasting.  The creamed farro was also not great tasting.  The pickled rhubarb, while interesting, was very strong.  Like I said, some people may find it wonderful, but my personal preference didn't really enjoy it.  But my wife has always loved her meals.  She had the salmon and said it was wonderful.

text: Came here on a solo trip to Fargo. Made a last minute reservation and the person on the phone taking taking was very friendly. The bar was a nice setup, and the bar tender was helpful in guiding me through their drinks and the menu. Once I sat down, the server was very attentive and personable. Food was fantastic - I had a four course meal and each course was solid and a perfect portion - not too much, not too little. It definitely wasn't cheap, but the cost was less than I expected and I found it to be a reasonable value for the meal I had received. Would definitely go back again.

text: Only OK. Everything was just a little off, not enough to be bad, but not great. Bread with the cheese plate and charcuterie was cold and seemed almost stale. Lemon cake dessert was pretty flavorless and lacked any lightness or brightness I would expect from lemons, although the accompanying lemon sorbet was amazing. Our server was good, but after very clearly telling her that my partner had a nut allergy, the server didn't think to mention that there were nuts on the dessert. The burger was a rather soggy mess, but the flavor was fine. The fries were not crisp and fresh, but they were OK. Again, nothing was exactly bad but thoroughly underwhelming. They have some great cocktails and a good atmosphere, but I'm just not excited to go back there to eat.

text:
Food was delicious. Service was polite. Seating was bad ... 2 of us sat in the comfy clam seat and the other two were in separate seats pushed away from each other and against the table because other seating was too close to us. Even more awkward was whenever a waiter tried to come by us, we had to constantly readjust our seats.
The temperature was really cold for us that sat in separate seats. Lighting was really dark. We were seated in the back of the restaurant and had made reservations earlier that week.
Decor was okay, the clam seats was pretty hokey.

Was happy to finally eat here because I heard such great things about the food, which was good. Just the rest I was disappointed with.

text: My wife, Tamara, and I dined at Mezzaluna on Friday night, Oct 7.  We live in the Twin Cities and have dined at its best restaurants, but this gem in Fargo is as good or better than any of them. The ambiance and service were wonderful and the food delicious.  My wife had the salmon and I had the rib eye.  Both were truly exceptional, both in presentation, preparation, and taste.  We look forward to returning the next time we visit Fargo.

text: The drinks: we had an assortment of cocktails, and while I totally forgot the names of any of them (which is ok, because the happy hour drinks seem to change frequently), they were all really, really good. At around $7 each, they were also a great value. The food: everything we had was amazing. I will start out with the "bruschetta," which should really be labeled as a charcuterie plate, as that's how it's presented (quite few different meats and assorted roasted/picked veggies, plus some bread)...whatever it's called on the menu, it's absolutely amazing. We also really enjoyed the walleye tacos  (also super yummy), the seared tuna (a smaller dish but also really tasty), and the happy hour burger + sweet potato tots (absolutely HUGE for $7.50).

text:
Amazing atmosphere, service and food.  We stopped for half priced apps and drinks for Happy Hour and really enjoyed the experience.  The truffled grilled cheese was amazing, the smoked beet tartare was average (good, but nothing really stood out for flavor) and the seared sea scallops melted in my wife's mouth.  The place was packed by 6 on a Friday night.  Another patron we started a conversation with said that the excellent service came from a staff assembled from the best of the high end restaurants downtown.  I highly recommend a stop for a meal and/or drinks.

text: Food simply was not good, and certainly not prepared as requested. The server was very nice and quite appologetic, but that really did not improve the dining experience. Mezzaluna has the reputation of being variable -- you sometimes have a good meal and sometimes a bad one. Out of the three times I have been there, one time was good -- the other two times I would have done better at McDonald's. I will not be going back -- there are too many really good restaurants in F/M where you can spend (much) less money, get better food, and have an all-around fine dining experience.

There was so many awesome drinks to order from, so our server said he would surprise me with a drink and it was amazing and very well made (it was a flambÃ©ed whiskey drink that I can't remember the name of it sadly). text: Whether you have just one night in Fargo, or an eternity, this is an experience not to be missed! Mezzaluna is top notch, for any city. And, not to take anything away from the food, because it was all spectacular; but it is the Service that puts a dining experience at Fargo's Mezzaluna up there with some of the best restaurants I've enjoyed across the USA. The Service is simply outstanding: Our Server, Hannah, was intelligent, personable, perfectly attentive, and expert in all of her duties, from beginning to end. I strongly suggest requesting a table in Hannah's section when you book your reservation. 5-Star food across the board too: Be sure to try the bruschetta appetizer, which is done like no other. Mezzaluna has my highest recommendation. The Service at this restaurant is almost reason enough to make a trip to Fargo.

text:
Sometime last year during a dark blue period I adopted a young african boy off of the television for as little as $5 a month. We never really met, we never really spoke and we surely hadn't ever bonded. It only made the blues darker and the nights longer. I wanted to change that, mostly for my own ego, as I suspected he had no idea where all of this loose change was flowing in from.
I received a photograph of "Mansuila" in the post after my first contribution to his new life and felt firm about taking it with me for a dinner alone to mend our ideas over a cool and cohesive diner.
We started with the Korv Sausage, Masuila was taken a back by the distribution of flavours. Poor people often only get the model the tongues taste buds active during each meal, I am sure that his whole tongue must have been a buzz with delight.
He couldn't handle the next dish we ordered and freaked out a bit, or the photo did. We had a sharp direct conversation where I threatened to stop exchanging my empty bottles to put him through school and feed his entire family.
The night was a bust but the dishes were a must.

Not necessarily a great place for your first  meal in America but it is an amazing place to share and bond none the less.

127/127 would do again!

text: Good service, awesome food! The drinks we got (Pimmlet and an apple-based bartender's special) were fabulous. I got the Scotch eggs and scallops, which were on a bed of some sort of delicious puree. It tasted like a creamy tomato soup. The scallops were yummy. The Scotch eggs are good if you like chorizo. My boyfriend got the flank steak. It was super tasty. However, save room for dessert. Seriously. We got the coconut bread pudding, and it was jaw-droppingly good. If it's happy hour, definitely go. I would definitely come back!

text: We made reservations to Mezzaluna with the hopes of eating at an "high end" restaurant and we experienced the complete opposite. Upon arrival, the restaurant was very noisy. We were confused as to why a "high end" restaurant sounded like a bar. Food was very bland and poor quality. Service was great can't complain about that. I ordered the crab stuffed Walley with lentils and it was very bland. My guy ordered prime rib. The quality of meat was very tough to cut into but tasted ok. Upon leaving we noticed a guest with sweat pants and flip flop came in to dine. It's just surprsing to us seeing some of the patrons dressed down when it's supposed to be a "high end" restaurant. Not that it bothered us but Fargo, ND really need to step up its definition  of a "high end" establishment. After leaving Mezzaluna we went to a Taco truck. That says a lot.

text: Nice staff and the scenery/atmosphere of the restaurant is great! However, I was not impressed with the food. I'm from the East coast  (Jersey and lived in Atlanta) and travelled to many different places with top notch foods and I heard about this place from a coworker of mine. So far since I've been living in ND for 5 years, I have been to Sky's in Grand Forks, The Hodo in Fargo, and Usher' s house in Moorhead, MN and they're on the same scale with Mezzaluna's, being classy dinning and my experience was GREAT at these other restaurants. So, I figured Mezzaluna's can be added to my list but unfortunately not. I made a reservation for a post-Valentine's day outing. I had Filet mignon and it was ok and my date had Leg of lamb and hers was very chard and a bit under cooked to the point where she couldn't finish it. Our waitress saw our reaction  (which is commendable on her part) and offered a free desert, which is fair. We selected the Carmel Apple pie with vanilla ice cream. Thinking it would be nice and warm, with the ice cream melting on top...to my biggest disappointment, it wasn't warm at all! It was cold and bitter! I was shocked! Who serves cold apple pie with vanilla ice cream?? Even McDonald's Apple pie is served warm and places like chain restaurants such as Red Lobster serve their pies nice and warm. I was pretty upset, especially money wise! But nonetheless, it was my first time going and my last unfortunately. If you're into classy dining and looking for great food to come out of it, I suggest the Hodo and Usher's House as the go to spots in the Fargo-Moorhead area. Thanks!

Great place for a special occasion and also simply to celebrate dining in a restaurant again, they have the space to do so safely.

text:
This is my second visit to The Starving Rooster and both have been amazing. The service, the food, and the available alcohol have been top notch. I've enjoyed their bruschetta, Cuban panini, and the Chipotle Chicken sandwich and was quite pleased. They have bottomless mimosas for brunch on Sunday, and their on top beer/cider selection is great. No complaints!

And for those that look for good music while partaking of tasty cuisine, this is the place to come. They've got great beats to keep you grooving through your meal.

I'll definitely be back!

text: For a positive note, I'll say that the ambiance was pretty awesome, very urban and social. It's a great spot if you're looking for an upbeat kind of place to hang out with friends. Very busy on this Friday night. There were no available tables so we were offered a seat at the bar. We accepted, even though neither of us drinks alcohol, because we were hungry & wanted to get served faster. Our waiter was the bartender and must not have been having a very good night, because she seemed put out having to serve us. I wish there had been some non-alcoholic mocktails on the menu, but we were told there were none, just typical soda fountain drinks. The food was okay, but not incredible. The bread on my Cuban Pork sandwich was pretty thick and over-toasted, which made it a little painful to bite. Maybe next time I'll try one of their pizzas instead.

text: After a great first experience, they RUINED themselves for us! We really liked our first visit... But it went down from there. We were told on our first visit that they would love to host our party of 12, that we just needed to call it in. We called and were told to call back in a few days. We called back. We were told yes, but please call back that day to hold a table that night. So we called that day... This time a manager told us "No, we don't do that, just come in and see if we can host you." So, when we got there they said they would seat us in "maybe an hour." So, we went to Sammy's. There we had a GREAT meal. Wonderful appetizers, pizza, and pasta!

text:
Food was pretty good but the service was not good at all. We placed our order with the waitress; an appetizer, some drinks and our main course. Our apps and drinks came out promptly and we enjoyed them. We then waited for 40 minutes before the SAME waitress asked if we had ordered any entrees. We explained that we had, and repeated our order. It became pretty obvious that our waitress had not put our main courses into the system and that we would be waiting a while longer. Iâ€™ve worked in the industry and understand these things happen. However, no apology or no mention of the inconvenience is unacceptable in my opinion and just awful service.

There was one waiter who we liked but other than that all of the other staff was rude. Do better.

text:
The location and the interior were awesome. Super trendy. There was no wait. We walked right in, got seated and ordered.

We ordered:
deviled eggs; they were good.
Creme bruleed French toast; pretty okay.
Breakfast pizza; it was pizza with scrambled eggs, it was okay.
Caprese Benny w/ potatoes; the Benedict was okay, my hollandaise sauce was a bit broken and the potatoes were very over done.
Artichoke dip; so good!!!
My sister had a Caesar; she said it was too spicey. And she not one to turn away or call anything "too spicey".

I had a cold brewed coffee; it was not good. I re-ordered a different drink. Our waiter wasn't pleased when i asked for a different drink. I love cold brewed coffee, I'm not an expert but it just wasn't good.

The ambiance was awesome.
The service was meh okay-ish.
The food could use some work.
It wasn't terrible, it wasn't the absolute best.

Will I go back? Maybe ðŸ˜

text:
I am not big on doing rants. But I am highly disapointed in my experience. I was recommended to this establishment by people in my home state and also at my hotel when I arrived in Minot for business. Upon arrival for lunch last week, my client and I were greeted promptly. The rest of our experience was like night and day. The first server, short dark curly haired lady whom i didnt get her name (wish i had) that came to our table seemed very irritated by my clients questions about the menu, beer ect. We shrugged it off and proceded to order our food and some standard domestic beer.... (Would have liked to hear about other options...but apparently our questions were too much at the time for her).
We had ordered an app that was delivered by another server who was a complete 180 from the original lady that we had. She was able to answer a few questions about some beer that was on tap and even went as far as to bring us a sample with a smile! Sweet. Food came and was delicious thankfully because our the curly haired server dropped our food off with a puff and didnt even ask if we wanted any condiments. So why a 1 star? Not the end of the world so far right? Well half way thru our meal the table across from us received something wrong on their meal. They did not seem too upset and the other server was prompt to fixing her mistake... Not awful until said curly haired server went off on the poor girl in front of other patrons and even mumbled a derogatory comment under her breath as other the worker walked away. Everyone in the area was left feeling uncomfortable. It was very unprofessional and I am assuming the dark haired gal must be in some sort of management position, which to me says alot about this establishment. I am embarassed I brought my client here and strongly suggest to others to be hesitant before doing so.

text:
Disappointed, we used to love the Rooster and never had a bad meal before today.  We've tried to stop there several times recently and they were either closed or had private parties.

Today we stopped by and they were luckily open, only to be incredibly disappointed by the food and service.  First, we were sat right next to the kitchen at a table (never given the option of the open booths) and it was LOUD.  Second, our waitress had the attitude that she would've liked to be anywhere but at work (we saw her twice, once to take our order, and once to drop off our bill).  Third, the food was just plain bad!!!  My wife loves their meatball sandwich, it was dry NO SAUCE, just meatballs!!!  I got one of their brick oven pizzas, it was doughy and undercooked.  We couldn't even flag someone down, while it was busy the staff wasn't hustling so much that they overlooked us, there was a group of them hanging out at the booth by the restrooms.  Couldnt get anyones attention, they just ignored everything.  Finally, they are offering a reduced menu because of "COVID" so good luck if your favorite meal didn't make their cut.

This was it for our family, we won't be returning  to the Rooster.  There's plenty of other places opening up in Minot that have better food and service.

text:
This place has the best pizza in town that I have tried so far and the bar offers some pretty good draft beer.

The atmosphere and staff are great every time we visit.  I tried the "starving rooster" pizza when I visited and it was one of the best pizza I have ever tried.

Aside from pizza they offer some interesting cuisine plates and they give an interesting twist to traditional wings than your ordinary place.

If you are new to town you should definitely give this place a try.

text: This place has some very cool history which you can read on their websight. I love the food here and the service has never been bad. I like the pizzas and flatbreads which are made in a brick oven. On this occasion I tried the ceasar salad and the pork belly tacos (they are small like street taco size) Sorry it is almost gone in the picture but I was too hungry to wait. It comes with a jalapeno slaw and a corn and bean salsa with just the right amount of pork. The meat was flavorful and tender. I paired it with a pineapple sage martini. The flavor was excellent! Just the right amount of everything!

text: We went to The Starving Rooster for our anniversary. It was perfect! We went on a happy hour social for 1/2 price wine which was a pleasant surprise. I was very happy with the quality and quantity of food we got. We went all out ordering an app, two entrees, and the dessert shooter sampler. text: The Starving Rooster is a modern must-dine destination for anyone living in or visiting Minot. It brings an atmosphere of openness and community that you won't find in too many other restaurants in Minot. It has an industrial style design and great brunch options. It can be good for groups of up to 25-30 people if you call ahead and reserve a party. Whenever I'm back in town this is one restaurant that I will always hit up!

text: Decent food. Nice atmosphere. Was first time there. Thought the pizza my son ordered was a little lacking on toppings, but still good. The prime rib stroganoff was ok, but think it would be better with a good sour cream base sauce. My wife ordered the Steak sandwich which she thought was very good. Bavarian pretzels were good, although you only get two on the order. (there was three of us)  The Bruschetta was very good. Price was reasonable.

text: First thing you notice walking through the door is the warm atmosphere. It feels like a place with a rich history. Comfortable seating, friendly and knowledgeable staff, oh, and AMAZING food. Everything is fresh, and served piping hot. Service was top notch. The roasted artichoke dip is a must try. Our server Erin was absolutely perfect. Drink selection is very vast and diverse. Tried a blackberry pear hard cider that our hostess recommended, enjoyed it a lot. Definitely going to be a regular.

text: We went to eat there this evening and the food and service was horrible. The waitress took forever to acknowledge that we were sitting there, when we ordered drinks we also ordered an appetizer which came out when our meal was almost complete. The soup of the day had good flavor but was more the consistency of chili. Our pizza was dry and barely even warm. We were charged for an extra side of ranch so all in all very disappointed. We will not be going back.

text: The place to be in Minot from 4-10.  We had the Starving Rooster pizza.  Enough for two people, but I ordered the Cuban.  The cuban sand wasn't bad, but really, order the pizza and enjoy a slice of heaven with beer.  Staff and management are the best I've ever seen.  The wait line starts just after 5, but worth the wait.  Parking is old school but don't let that fool ya.  You won't find many better restaurants in the country when you add up all things here.  Effort and smiles go a long way, not to mention the best pizza we've had in a while, and we're from Chicago and haven't found a decent pizza in two years.  Never ever thought we'd find it a stones throw from Canada, eh?

text: A great addition to Minot. Any meal is awesome, but the brunch is outstanding. They serve local beers as well as old favorites. The pizzas and sandwiches and flat breads are worth the calories. The Cuban has some good spice. The thai chx lettuce wraps are a good light option. The thai pizza and the veggie one are both amazing as well. They also have an excellent artichoke dip and make some pretty decent mules. Great atmosphere. Can get pretty busy at peak times.

I wouldn't expect this kind of a place to even be in ND; it competes with other great pizza places we've experienced in big cities. I would def go to the Starving Rooster again!

The only time it is dark like that is when it is old.

text:
Ordered a flatbread and traditional style pizza. All toppings and sauces had good flavor.

Flatbread was great, with a tasty browned, crisped crust.

The traditional was flat, in flavor and texture. The crumb wasn't very open, with a clear gum line where dough didn't rise. Maybe under proved?

Don't know if they use a long ferment of several days or a short one.

Atmosphere and staff were wonderful.

text: Overall it's pretty meh. The drink selection does not match the expectation that the decor sets. The beers are overwhelmingly ales and IPAs with little else available. The food is unexciting. The shrimp and crab stuffed mushrooms tasted more like breadcrumbs than anything else. The flatbread pizza crust was way too thin and crispy, the toppings were scant and too largely chopped, and they used dry crumbled Parmesan on it ether than fresh grated. It's probably better off just going to the Olive Garden.
